        "excerpt": "Now one of the servants of Saul was there that day, detained before the LORD; and his name was Doeg the Edomite.",
        "body": "Verse 7 is a single verse, but it is the chapter's pivot. The narrator inserts it between the bread transaction (vv.4-6) and the sword request (vv.8-9) without explanation or editorial comment. Doeg is identified with four precise details: he is one of Saul's servants (political alignment), he is an Edomite (ethnic outsider, descendant of Esau, traditional adversary of Israel), he is Saul's chief shepherd (a position of trust), and he is 'detained before the LORD' (present at Nob for some religious purpose — possibly fulfilling a vow, or undergoing a purification rite, or consulting the priest).\n\nThe irony of Doeg's presence is layered. He is at the sanctuary for a religious reason, yet his presence there will be the instrument of the sanctuary's destruction. He is 'before the LORD' — the same phrase used of the bread in verse 6 — while simultaneously becoming the means by which the LORD's priests will be slaughtered. The narrator's precision (naming him, his ethnicity, his office, his exact location on that exact day) serves one purpose: to ensure the reader recognizes him in 22:9-10 when he volunteers the information to Saul. The chapter does not need Doeg to act; it only needs the reader to see him.\n\nChuck Swindoll (*David: A Man of Passion and Destiny*) notes that Doeg represents the kind of figure who appears in Scripture at moments of moral crisis — present, silent, observing, and deadly. His appearance here is the narrator's way of showing that David's deception has consequences he cannot control or foresee. Providence allows Doeg to be there; David's deception gives Doeg something worth reporting. The two causes — divine permission and human sin — run together without either excusing the other.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ne'etsar lifnei YHWH* (detained before the LORD, v.7) — *atsar* can mean restrained, detained, or held. The same root appears in v.5 of the men being 'kept' from women. The verbal echo links Doeg's religious detention with the ritual purity discussion — both involve the concept of being held in a particular condition before the LORD."
