        "body": "David's request for a weapon in verse 8 deepens the deception: 'the king's matter was urgent' — still the fiction of verse 2. Ahimelech's response is one of the Old Testament's most theologically compressed moments. He reaches behind the ephod and produces the sword of Goliath. The ephod was the high priest's principal vestment, used for seeking God's oracular guidance (cf. 1 Samuel 23:9; 30:7). That Goliath's sword rests behind it suggests it has been preserved as a votive trophy — a monument to the LORD's victory at Elah stored in the LORD's sanctuary.\n\nThe scene's irony operates on multiple levels. David killed Goliath by faith, with a sling stone, declaring that 'the battle is the LORD's' (17:47). The sword he took from the fallen giant was the trophy of that faith. Now, years later, the same David — bereft of faith at this moment, operating entirely by deception and fear — retrieves the symbol of his greatest faith-act to use in a crisis his fear has created. The sword is unchanged; it is still 'the sword of Goliath the Philistine, whom you killed in the valley of Elah.' The past victory is real and permanent. But the man holding it is not presently the same man who won it.\n\nDavid's recognition of the sword ('there is none like it; give it to me,' v.9) is haunting. He knows it immediately. The encounter with the trophy of Elah in the sanctuary of Nob is the chapter's closest moment to self-awareness — but it does not produce repentance or prayer. David takes the sword and continues south toward Gath. Howard Hendricks (*Living by the Book*) observed that trophies of past victory can become substitutes for present trust; David's retrieval of Goliath's sword in the absence of any inquiry of the LORD illustrates the principle precisely.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ephod* (v.9) — the priestly garment associated with divine consultation (cf. 1 Samuel 23:9; 30:7, where David 'inquires of the LORD' using the ephod through the priest). That David retrieves a weapon from behind the ephod without ever asking the ephod's function — without inquiring of the LORD — is one of the chapter's sharpest silences."
